],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"Married a Yale-educated 'quaint and erratic' preacher","body":"Cynthia married Rev. Allen Olcott in 1792 — a Yale College 1768 graduate settled at the Farmington Presbyterian Church in 1787. After four years his preaching was deemed 'quaint and erratic' enough that he was dismissed and never settled at any other church."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Settled with Allen on a South Manchester farm","body":"After his Farmington dismissal Allen returned to his native East Hartford and then settled with Cynthia on a farm at South Manchester, Connecticut. Family stories suggest his farming methods were as unique as his preaching had been. He died there in April 1811, leaving Cynthia a widow with five children ranging from eight to eighteen."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Remarried Capt. Samuel Alvord at fifty-three","body":"Two years after Allen's death Cynthia remarried — Capt. Samuel Alvord of East Hartford, on 14 January 1813. The couple lived at East Hartford until her own death in June 1827. Through her first marriage's daughter Cynthia, her line married back into the Talcott-Hooker convergence."}],"slug":"cynthia-hooker-1760"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}